FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - KIRGHIZIA (KYRGYZSTAN)
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: Tue, 13 Jul 1999 12:11:11 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Tass Asian news-in-brief column for Tuesday, 13 Jul 1999
Story Filed: Monday, July 12, 1999 4:44 PM EST

BISHKEK -- An outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease has been registered in the
Kara-Buurin district of Kirghizia's Talass region. According to Alexei
Yermolov of the republic's Ministry for Emergency Situations, nearly 400
head of cattle have been infected with this contagious disease. All
domestic animal markets have been closed in the region, and mass
vaccination of all domestic animals has begun. Specialists from the
ministries of water resources and agriculture are working in the district
and a quarantine
service has been organised.
[Kirghizia (former name for Kyrgyzstan was Kirghiz Soviet Socialist
Republic) is an independent republic located in Asia, bordered by
Kazakhstan to the north, Tajikistan and China to the southwest and
southeast respectively, Uzbekistan to the west and China to the east. The
Talas region is in the northwestern portion of the country bordering on
Kazakhstan. - MPP]
---
Marjorie P. Pollack, M.D.
pollackmp@mindspring.com
***
[A check of the OIE reports revealed the following:
12 February 1999
Vol. 12 - No. 5
FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN KYRGYSZTAN
(Date of last previously reported outbreak: April 1997).
Emergency report
Translation of a communication received on 10 February 1999 from Dr B.E.
Dardanov,
Director General of Veterinary Services, Bishkek:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 10 October 1998.
Estimated date of first infection: 8 October 1998.
Outbreaks:
Location No. of outbreaks
Kant district, Chuya region 3 localities*
* Milemfan, Ak-Kuduk villages and 3rd MIS Division
Description of affected population: the outbreaks contain sheep, cattle,
horses, dogs and swine. [Horses & dogs are not susceptible. - MHJ] Farm
animals are kept indoors.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species Nos
susceptible cases deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
bovine 365 37 0/0/0
ovine 978 ... 0/0/0
caprine 67 ... 0/0/0
swine 31 ... 0/0/0

Diagnosis: the disease is expressed in a mild clinical form.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Veterinary Institute for
Scientific
Research and Control.
B. Diagnostic tests used: inoculation to animals, complement fixation
inhibition test, immunodiffusion test, complement fixation test.
C. Causal agent: virus type O194.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: the source of infection is
thought to be forage, or clinically or subclinically affected animals
purchased from markets and originating from neighbouring countries.
B. Mode of spread: contact with sick animals or contaminated feed.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine of the affected
localities and movement control inside the country; emergency vaccination
of all susceptible animals. All the animals in the outbreaks has been
vaccinated.
[The explanation for this outbreak is generic and indicates that the source
is either unknown or not being shared. - MHJ]
***
Kazakhstan, OIE Report, 11 December 1998, Vol. 11 - No. 49 and prior reports.
Extract from the monthly report of Kazakhstan for October 1998, received on
7 December 1998 from Dr Shakhaidar J. Tursunkulov, President of the
Veterinary Committee, Ministry of Agriculture, Astana: In view of the
lifting of quarantine measures in Dzhambul (Jambyl) region on 25 October
1998, Kazakhstan should be considered free from foot and mouth disease in
cattle.
Location No. of outbreaks
South Kazakhstan region 1
Dzhambul (Jambyl) region 2
Kzyl-Orda region 1
Alma-Ata (Almaty) region 1
